; let-binding-band — a do-let binds its name for the REST of the do, four-way.
;
; The bug this guards: a top-level (do (let NAME VAL) .. BODY) where BODY reads NAME.
; fkwu's top-level (do ...) used to re-enter the top parser per inner form, which has
; no let-binding and overwrote the root each iteration, so the binding was lost — BODY
; read an unbound name (a list let -> len 0, an int let -> 0). The three walkers bind
; (let name val) into the do's shared scope and read it back. Canonical `let` is TWO-ARG
; (observe/wav-sense.fk: "let is two-arg only; binds for the rest of its do"); the kernel
; now binds it identically whether the do is nested or the top-level root form.
;
; Verdict 31 when every claim lands — all four kernels must agree:
;   1   a LIST let survives: (len p) == 2                    (the head case: list lost -> 0)
;   2   the bound list is intact at its head: (head p) == 10
;   4   ...and at an interior index:           (nth p 1) == 20
;   8   an INT let survives:   (add q 1) == 6                (even a scalar binding was lost)
;   16  a let bound FROM an earlier let chains: r=(add q 1)=6, s=(add r 1)=7, s == 7
(do
    (let p (list 10 20))
    (let q 5)
    (let r (add q 1))
    (let s (add r 1))
    (let c0 (if (eq (len p) 2) 1 0))
    (let c1 (if (eq (head p) 10) 2 0))
    (let c2 (if (eq (nth p 1) 20) 4 0))
    (let c3 (if (eq (add q 1) 6) 8 0))
    (let c4 (if (eq s 7) 16 0))
    (add c0 (add c1 (add c2 (add c3 c4)))))
